# Clean Code (CHOLE sport)

Prioritize long-term maintainability over quick-and-dirty fixes.

## Modularity
- Keep logic and UI separated.
- Extract complex functions into `src/lib/`, `src/hooks/`, or `src/services/` — not inside components.
- Components should orchestrate; utilities should compute.

## Reusability
- Avoid hardcoding URLs, copy, thresholds, and config in JSX.
- Use props, constants (e.g. `src/data/`, `src/lib/`), and shared types.
- Prefer composable, configurable components.

## Consistency
- Follow existing project structure:
  - `src/components/site/` — page/section UI
  - `src/lib/` — pure utilities
  - `src/context/` — shared state
  - `src/data/` — static data and types
  - `src/routes/` — route shells only
- If logic is reused in 2+ places, move it to a shared module.

## Maintenance
- Before changing code, ask: does this add technical debt?
- If a file exceeds ~200 lines or mixes concerns, refactor into smaller pieces.
- Suggest refactoring when touching messy areas — don't only patch symptoms.

## Documentation
- Add brief comments only for non-obvious business rules or tricky logic.
- Don't comment what the code already says clearly.

## Examples

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — business logic in component
function CartPage() {
  const shipping = subtotal >= 350 ? 0 : 35;
}

// ✅ GOOD — utility + constant
import { getShippingCost, FREE_SHIPPING_THRESHOLD } from "@/lib/checkout";
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — hardcoded URL in JSX
<a href="https://wa.me/972542366279">

// ✅ GOOD — shared constant
import { WHATSAPP_URL } from "@/lib/contact";
```
